.TH "GREP\-FIND\-UNICODE\-WRAPPER" "1" "January 2020" "helper-scripts" "helper-scripts Manual"

.SH "NAME"
\fBgrep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper\fR \- Find suspicious Unicode characters using grep semantics
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
\fBgrep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper\fR [\fIGREP_OPTIONS\fR\|\.\|\.\|\.] [\fIPATH\fR\|\.\|\.\|\.]
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
\fBgrep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper\fR is a thin wrapper around \fBgrep\fR(1) that runs four pre\-configured passes against the supplied input, looking for suspicious Unicode characters: non\-ASCII bytes, Right\-to\-Left Override and related bidirectional control characters, and ASCII control characters\. Matching paths (with line numbers) are printed on standard output\.
.P
It exists to apply a fixed set of vetted regex patterns \- the same set referenced by the Unicode Trojan and "Trojan Source" advisories \- across whatever files the user names, while still letting the user inject their own \fBgrep\fR flags such as \fB\-\-recursive\fR\.
.P
This tool is \fBpipeline\-friendly\fR, not user\-friendly\. End users who just want to know whether a file or directory contains anything unsafe should use \fBtext\-safety\-scan\-file\fR(1) instead\.
.SS "Detection set"
Each invocation runs four \fBgrep\fR passes (results are merged and de\-duplicated):
.IP "1." 4
Non\-ASCII bytes via \fB[^\ex00\-\ex7F]\fR (Perl regex)\.
.IP "2." 4
Non\-ASCII characters via \fB[^[:ascii:]]\fR (Perl regex)\.
.IP "3." 4
The bidirectional / formatting control characters listed in the Trojan Source advisory: \fBU+061C\fR, \fBU+200E\fR, \fBU+200F\fR, \fBU+202A\fR\-\fBU+202E\fR, \fBU+2066\fR\-\fBU+2069\fR\.
.IP "4." 4
ASCII control characters (\fBU+0000\fR\-\fBU+0008\fR, \fBU+000B\fR\-\fBU+000C\fR, \fBU+000E\fR\-\fBU+001F\fR, \fBU+007F\fR)\.
.IP "" 0
.P
\fB\-\-binary\-files=text\fR is set so that NUL and backspace bytes are matched even in files \fBgrep\fR would otherwise classify as binary\.
.SS "Forwarding user flags"
Anything passed on the command line is forwarded to \fBgrep\fR after the internal options are applied\. Common additions:
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-\-recursive\fR (or \fB\-r\fR) to descend into directories\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB\-l\fR / \fB\-L\fR selectors are not useful here; the wrapper already uses \fB\-\-files\-with\-matches\fR\.
.IP "" 0
.SS "End\-of\-options ('\-\-')"
This wrapper does \fBnot\fR insert \fB\-\-\fR between its own arguments and the user's\. That is by design: users may need to pass \fB\-\-\fR themselves as part of their \fBgrep\fR invocation\. It remains the responsibility of the caller to supply \fB\-\-\fR when separating options from filenames\.
.SH "RETURN VALUES"
These intentionally mirror \fBgrep\fR(1):
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB0\fR Matches were found\. Matching paths are printed\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB1\fR No matches were found\. Nothing is printed\.
.IP "\(bu" 4
\fB2\fR \fBgrep\fR reported a syntax or I/O error\. The wrapper exits with the same code\.
.IP "" 0
.P
This is the right contract for use in pipelines and shell scripts (\fBif grep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper \-r src/; then \|\.\|\.\|\.\fR), but it is the opposite of what most other safety tools return (clean = 0)\. If you want "non\-zero means unsafe was found", use \fBtext\-safety\-scan\-file\fR(1)\.
.SH "EXAMPLES"
Scan a single file:
.P
\fBgrep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper file\.txt\fR
.P
Scan a directory recursively:
.P
\fBgrep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper \-\-recursive src/\fR
.P
Use in a shell condition (note the inverted sense):
.P
\fBif grep\-find\-unicode\-wrapper \-\-recursive src/; then printf '%s\en' 'Suspicious characters found\.' >&2 exit 1 fi\fR
.SH "SEE ALSO"
text\-safety\-scan\-file(1), unicode\-show(1), grep(1)
.P
